docs.abstract: Senator Marco Rubio, Republican of Florida, has become a chief policy architect for the United States in a daring and risky campaign to dislodge Venezuela’s autocratic leader from power.
docs.snippet: Senator Marco Rubio, Republican of Florida, has become a chief policy architect for the United States in a daring and risky campaign to dislodge Venezuela’s autocratic leader from power.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — His hand chopping in the air, his voice stern and stalwart, he declared that it was time for the regional despot to go and warned of the consequences if he did not. With a commander in chief’s resolve, he vowed that the United States would do whatever it took to protect its own diplomats on the ground.

headline.main: On Venezuela, Rubio Assumes U.S. Role of Ouster in Chief
headline.print_headline: Rubio Driving U.S. Strategy In Venezuela

byline.original: By Peter Baker and Edward Wong

docs.abstract: The State Department’s decision to turn over assets and property to Juan Guaidó is part of a Trump Administration effort to oust President Nicolás Maduro.
docs.snippet: The State Department’s decision to turn over assets and property to Juan Guaidó is part of a Trump Administration effort to oust President Nicolás Maduro.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The State Department said Tuesday that it had given the Venezuelan opposition leader Juan Guaidó the right to control assets and property in the United States bank accounts of the government of Venezuela.

headline.main: Venezuelan Opposition Leader Guaidó Controls U.S. Bank Accounts, State Dept. Says
headline.print_headline: State Dept. Says Guaidó  Controls U.S. Accounts

docs.abstract: The arrest of Meng Wanzhou of Huawei has set off a diplomatic crisis, and China is pressuring Canada to release her, but the U.S. is moving ahead with an extradition request.
docs.snippet: The arrest of Meng Wanzhou of Huawei has set off a diplomatic crisis, and China is pressuring Canada to release her, but the U.S. is moving ahead with an extradition request.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The United States plans to formally request within a week that Canada extradite a top Huawei executive to stand trial for charges related to violating American sanctions on Iran.

headline.main: U.S. Will Ask Canada to Extradite Huawei Executive
headline.print_headline: U.S. Says It Will Ask Canada to Extradite Telecom Executive

docs.abstract: Mexico reluctantly agreed to accept the immigrants while their cases are considered in court. The move could substantially reduce the number of people trying to gain entry into the United States.
docs.snippet: Mexico reluctantly agreed to accept the immigrants while their cases are considered in court. The move could substantially reduce the number of people trying to gain entry into the United States.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration, mired in a battle with Congress over funding of a border wall, announced on Thursday that the United States would begin requiring people seeking asylum at the southwest border to wait in Mexico for a court ruling on their cases.

headline.main: Migrants Seeking Asylum Must Wait in Mexico, Trump Administration Says
headline.print_headline: Administration’s Waiting Room for Migrants Seeking Asylum: Mexico

docs.abstract: The 248-to-181 vote fell short of the two-thirds majority needed, shifting the fight over the president’s emergency declaration to the courts.
docs.snippet: The 248-to-181 vote fell short of the two-thirds majority needed, shifting the fight over the president’s emergency declaration to the courts.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The House on Tuesday failed to overturn President Trump’s first veto, leaving the declaration of a national emergency at the southwestern border intact despite the bipartisan passage of a resolution attempting to nullify the president’s circumvention of Congress to fund his border wall.

headline.main: House Fails to Override Trump’s Veto, Preserving National Emergency Order
headline.print_headline: House Fails to Override Trump’s Veto, Preserving National Emergency Order

docs.abstract: Senator Mitch McConnell, the majority leader, conceded that he could not stop the Senate from overturning President Trump’s national emergency declaration.
docs.snippet: Senator Mitch McConnell, the majority leader, conceded that he could not stop the Senate from overturning President Trump’s national emergency declaration.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Mitch McConnell, the majority leader, conceded on Monday that he could not stave off final passage of a resolution overturning President Trump’s national emergency declaration, setting up a rebuke to Mr. Trump amid signs that the president’s grip even on his own party in Congress may be slipping.

headline.main: Trump’s Grip Shows Signs of Slipping as Senate Prepares to Block Wall Emergency
headline.print_headline: Trump’s Grip Seen Waning In the Senate

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — She paused to maintain her composure as she spoke. She recalled the attacks, and how her reports of them were handled. The despair, she said, almost made her leave the military.

headline.print_headline: Air Force Pioneer Turned Senator Says Superior Officer Raped Her

docs.abstract: Senate Republicans believe the Green New Deal is a political disaster for Democrats, and they will make them vote on it — possibly many times.
docs.snippet: Senate Republicans believe the Green New Deal is a political disaster for Democrats, and they will make them vote on it — possibly many times.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Mitch McConnell, the majority leader, will force Democrats on Tuesday to take a stand on the Green New Deal and its ambitious goal of conquering climate change — after a long windup designed to drive a wedge between cautious Democratic senators and the liberal activists pushing for climate action.

headline.main: McConnell to Put Green New Deal to Test Vote in First of Many Showcases
headline.print_headline: G.O.P. Senses Opportunity in Green New Deal Vote

byline.original: By Lisa Friedman and Emily Cochrane

docs.abstract: Every House Democrat voted for a broadly worded resolution condemning “hateful expressions of intolerance,” but 23 Republicans voted no.
docs.snippet: Every House Democrat voted for a broadly worded resolution condemning “hateful expressions of intolerance,” but 23 Republicans voted no.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The House passed a resolution on Thursday that condemned anti-Semitism and other forms of bigotry. The resolution, written by House Democrats, began as an implicit response to comments made by Representative Ilhan Omar, Democrat of Minnesota, that were widely deemed anti-Semitic, but when some Democrats objected to singling her out, the resolution was broadened to condemn other forms of hatred.

headline.main: Why Some Republicans Voted Against the Antibigotry Resolution
headline.print_headline: G.O.P. House Members Explain Their ‘No’ Votes On Antibigotry Measure

byline.original: By Emily Cochrane and Catie Edmondson

docs.abstract: Mr. Hunter, accused of spending tens of thousands of dollars on personal expenses like family trips and tuition, became the second Republican congressman indicted this month.
docs.snippet: Mr. Hunter, accused of spending tens of thousands of dollars on personal expenses like family trips and tuition, became the second Republican congressman indicted this month.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Representative Duncan Hunter was indicted by a federal grand jury in San Diego on Tuesday after a monthslong criminal investigation into allegations that he spent tens of thousands of dollars in campaign funds on family trips to Hawaii and Italy, private school tuition for his children and even a $600 airline ticket for a pet rabbit.

headline.main: Representative Duncan Hunter Is Indicted, Accused of Misusing Campaign Funds
